 *
 * @section quickstart Getting Started
 *
 * @subsection build_sec Building from Source
 *
 * @code{.sh}
 * git clone https://github.com/QoroQuantum/maestro.git
 * cd maestro
 * chmod +x build.sh
 * ./build.sh
 * @endcode
 *
 * For detailed build options (GPU support, optional dependencies, etc.),
 * see the @ref md_INSTALL "Installation Guide".
 *
 * @subsection cpp_example C++ Example
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "maestrolib/Interface.h"
 *
 * int main() {
 *     // Define a simple Bell-state circuit in OpenQASM
 *     std::string qasm = R"(
 *         OPENQASM 2.0;
 *         include "qelib1.inc";
 *         qreg q[2];
 *         creg c[2];
 *         h q[0];
 *         cx q[0], q[1];
 *         measure q -> c;
 *     )";
 *
 *     // Let Maestro choose the best backend and execute
 *     MaestroLibrary lib;
 *     lib.LoadCircuitFromQasm(qasm);
 *     auto results = lib.Execute(1024);
 *     // results now contains measurement counts
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * @subsection py_example Python Example
 *
 * @code{.py}
 * import maestro
 *
 * qasm = """
 * OPENQASM 2.0;
 * include "qelib1.inc";
 * qreg q[2];
 * h q[0];
 * cx q[0], q[1];
 * """
 *
 * result = maestro.simple_execute(qasm, shots=1024)
 * print(f"Counts: {result['counts']}")
 * @endcode
 *
 * For a comprehensive walkthrough, see the @ref md_TUTORIAL "Tutorial".
 *
 * ---
 *
 * @section backends Simulation Backends
 *
 * Maestro integrates or wraps the following simulation technologies:
 *
 * | Category | Technology | Notes |
 * |----------|------------|-------|
 * | CPU Statevector | QCSim, Qiskit Aer | Full state-vector simulation |
 * | CPU MPS | QCSim, Qiskit Aer | Matrix Product State with configurable bond dimension |
 * | CPU Stabilizer | QCSim, Qiskit Aer | Efficient Clifford-only simulation |
 * | CPU Tensor Network | QCSim, Qiskit Aer | Tensor network contraction |
 * | CPU Pauli Propagator | QCSim | Pauli propagation simulation |
 * | CPU Extended Stabilizer | Qiskit Aer | Near-Clifford decomposition |
 * | GPU Statevector | NVIDIA cuStateVec | Via dynamic GPU library loading |
 * | GPU MPS | Custom CUDA | Custom GPU MPS implementation |
 * | GPU Tensor %Network | Custom CUDA | Tensor network simulation on GPU |
 * | GPU Pauli Propagator | Custom CUDA | Pauli propagation simulation on GPU |
 * | QuEST | QuEST library | CPU statevector with MPI distribution |
 * | Composite | p-block | Distributed state across sub-simulators |
 *
 * Each backend is accessed through a C++ adapter implementing the
 * @ref Simulators::ISimulator interface.
 *
 * ---
 *
 * @section quest_backend QuEST Backend
 *
 * Maestro supports the [QuEST](https://quest.qtechtheory.org/) simulator
 * as an alternative CPU backend. QuEST is loaded dynamically as a shared
 * library (`libmaestroquest`), so it is available only when the library
 * has been built and installed.
 *
 * QuEST natively supports **MPI-distributed statevector** simulation,
 * enabling execution across multiple nodes for larger qubit counts.
 *
 * QuEST only supports **Statevector** simulation. Attempting to use it
 * with MPS, Stabilizer, or other simulation types will raise an error.
 *
 * @subsection quest_init Initialisation
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "Simulators/Factory.h"
 *
 * // Initialise QuEST (all platforms)
 * bool questReady = Simulators::SimulatorsFactory::InitQuestLibrary();
 * if (questReady)
 *     std::cout << "QuEST loaded successfully" << std::endl;
 * @endcode
 *
 * @subsection quest_exec Running a Circuit with QuEST
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "maestrolib/Interface.h"
 * #include "Simulators/Factory.h"
 * #include "Simulators/State.h"
 *
 * void* maestro = GetMaestroObject();
 * Simulators::SimulatorsFactory::InitQuestLibrary();
 *
 * unsigned long int simHandle = CreateSimpleSimulator(2);
 *
 * // Switch to QuEST Statevector
 * RemoveAllOptimizationSimulatorsAndAdd(
 *     simHandle,
 *     static_cast<int>(Simulators::SimulatorType::kQuestSim),
 *     static_cast<int>(Simulators::SimulationType::kStatevector)
 * );
 *
 * const char* qasm =
 *     "OPENQASM 2.0;\n"
 *     "include \"qelib1.inc\";\n"
 *     "qreg q[2]; creg c[2];\n"
 *     "h q[0]; cx q[0], q[1];\n"
 *     "measure q -> c;\n";
 *
 * char* result = SimpleExecute(simHandle, qasm, "{\"shots\": 1024}");
 * // result JSON: {"counts": {"00": ~512, "11": ~512}, "simulator": "quest", ...}
 *
 * FreeResult(result);
 * DestroySimpleSimulator(simHandle);
 * @endcode
 *
 * @subsection quest_python QuEST in Python
 *
 * See the @ref python_guide "Python Guide" for QuEST usage from Python,
 * including `maestro.init_quest()` and `maestro.is_quest_available()`.
 *
 * ---
 *
 * @section gpu_backend GPU Backend
 *
 * @note The GPU backend is **not included** in the open-source version of
 * Maestro. Contact [Qoro Quantum](https://qoroquantum.de) for access.
 *
 * Maestro supports GPU-accelerated simulation via a dynamically-loaded
 * CUDA library (`libmaestro_gpu_simulators`). The GPU backend is
 * optional and loaded at runtime only when requested.
 *
 * Unlike QuEST, the GPU backend supports **multiple simulation types**:
 *
 * | SimulationType | GPU Support |
 * |----------------|-------------|
 * | `kStatevector` | ✅ |
 * | `kMatrixProductState` | ✅ |
 * | `kTensorNetwork` | ✅ |
 * | `kPauliPropagator` | ✅ |
 * | `kStabilizer` | ❌ |
 * | `kExtendedStabilizer` | ❌ |
 *
 * @subsection gpu_init Initialisation
 *
 * On Linux, `GetMaestroObject()` automatically attempts to load the GPU
 * library. You can also initialise it explicitly:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "Simulators/Factory.h"
 *
 * #ifdef __linux__
 * bool gpuReady = Simulators::SimulatorsFactory::InitGpuLibrary();
 * if (gpuReady)
 *     std::cout << "GPU library loaded" << std::endl;
 * #endif
 * @endcode
 *
 * @subsection gpu_exec Running a Circuit on GPU
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "maestrolib/Interface.h"
 * #include "Simulators/State.h"
 *
 * void* maestro = GetMaestroObject();
 * unsigned long int simHandle = CreateSimpleSimulator(2);
 *
 * // Switch to GPU + Statevector
 * RemoveAllOptimizationSimulatorsAndAdd(
 *     simHandle,
 *     static_cast<int>(Simulators::SimulatorType::kGpuSim),
 *     static_cast<int>(Simulators::SimulationType::kStatevector)
 * );
 *
 * const char* qasm =
 *     "OPENQASM 2.0;\n"
 *     "include \"qelib1.inc\";\n"
 *     "qreg q[2]; creg c[2];\n"
 *     "h q[0]; cx q[0], q[1];\n"
 *     "measure q -> c;\n";
 *
 * char* result = SimpleExecute(simHandle, qasm, "{\"shots\": 1024}");
 * // result JSON: {"counts": {...}, "simulator": "gpu_simulator", ...}
 *
 * FreeResult(result);
 * DestroySimpleSimulator(simHandle);
 * @endcode
 *
 * @subsection gpu_mps GPU MPS Example
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * // Switch to GPU + MPS
 * RemoveAllOptimizationSimulatorsAndAdd(
 *     simHandle,
 *     static_cast<int>(Simulators::SimulatorType::kGpuSim),
 *     static_cast<int>(Simulators::SimulationType::kMatrixProductState)
 * );
 *
 * char* result = SimpleExecute(simHandle, qasm, "{\"shots\": 1024}");
 * @endcode
 *
 * @subsection gpu_python GPU in Python
 *
 * See the @ref python_guide "Python Guide" for GPU usage from Python,
 * including `maestro.init_gpu()` and `maestro.is_gpu_available()`.
 *
 * @section auto_backend Automatic Backend Selection
 *
 * @note Automatic Backend Selection is a **closed-source** feature and is
 * not included in the open-source release of Maestro. Contact
 * [Qoro Quantum](https://qoroquantum.de) for access.
 *
 * Maestro's prediction engine:
 * 1. Extracts structural features from the circuit (gate density, entanglement
 *    locality, circuit width/depth)
 * 2. Uses a regression model trained on benchmark data
 * 3. Estimates relative runtimes across all available backends
 * 4. Selects the backend expected to be fastest on the current hardware
 *
 * The model normalises performance features to reduce hardware dependence
 * and can be recalibrated at installation time.
 *
 * @sa @ref estimators
 *
